2 SENATE BILL 742
1 Article – Health – General
2 Section 15–101(a), (h), and (i)
3 Annotated Code of Maryland
4 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
5 BY adding to
6 Article – Health – General
7 Section 15–103.9
8 Annotated Code of Maryland
9 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
10 Preamble
11 WHEREAS, The landmark decision of the U.S. Supreme Court in Olmstead v. L.C.
12 ex rel. Zimring, 527 U.S. 581 (1999) affirmed that unjustified segregation of individuals
13 with disabilities constitutes discrimination in violation of Title II of the federal Americans
14 with Disabilities Act; and
15 WHEREAS, The Olmstead decision established that people with disabilities have
16 the right to receive services in the most integrated setting appropriate to their needs and
17 that states must provide community–based services when such services are appropriate,
18 desired by the individual, and can be reasonably accommodated; and
19 WHEREAS, Individuals with intellectual and developmental disabilities are vital
20 members of Maryland’s communities, contributing meaningfully in workplaces, classrooms,
21 places of worship, neighborhoods, and civic life across the State; and
22 WHEREAS, The State of Maryland has demonstrated a longstanding commitment
23 to community inclusion by closing nearly all large public institutions for people with
24 intellectual and developmental disabilities and investing in supports that allow
25 Marylanders with disabilities to live, work, and thrive in the communities of their choosing,
26 with people they choose; and
27 WHEREAS, Despite this progress, barriers remain when administrative
28 inefficiencies and delays in Medicaid eligibility determinations or redeterminations cause
29 individuals to lose critical home– and community–based services or remain
30 institutionalized after they are medically ready for discharge; and
31 WHEREAS, Ensuring timely Medicaid eligibility determinations, preventing
32 procedural terminations, and protecting continuity of home– and community–based
33 services coverage are necessary to fulfill the promise of Olmstead and uphold Maryland’s
34 commitment to dignity, inclusion, and equality for all people with disabilities; and
35 WHEREAS, Maryland law requires the Developmental Disabilities Administration
36 and the Department of Disabilities to compile statewide and regional data from written
37 plans of habilitation, including barriers to community placement, and to incorporate the

SENATE BILL 742 3
1 data annually into the State’s Olmstead Plan together with recommendations for
2 addressing those barriers; now, therefore,
3 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
4 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
5 Article – Health – General
6 7–309.
7 (b) (1) An individual receiving Administration services who receives notice
8 from the Department that the individual has lost eligibility to receive Maryland Medical
9 Assistance Program services [shall have 90 days after the date on which the notification
10 letter was mailed to] MAY appeal the determination.
11 (2) If an individual appeals a loss of eligibility within the time period
12 required under [paragraph (1) of this subsection] § 42 C.F.R. 431.231, Administration
13 services for the individual shall continue uninterrupted until the outcome of the appeal is
14 complete.
15 (3) The Department shall ensure that providers of Administration services
16 to an individual affected by a loss of eligibility are notified of the individual’s loss of
17 eligibility when notice is sent to the individual.
18 (4) The Department shall ensure that providers, including coordinators of
19 community services, have the ability to automatically exchange electronic data with the
20 Department through an application program interface with the Department’s Long Term
21 Services and Supports software system.
22 15–101.
23 (a) In this title the following words have the meanings indicated.
24 (h) “Program” means the Maryland Medical Assistance Program.
25 (i) “Program recipient” means an individual who receives benefits under the
26 Program.
27 15–103.9.
28 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
29 INDICATED.
30 (2) “EX PARTE REDETERMINATION” MEANS A PROCESS BY WHICH
31 THE DEPARTMENT DETERMINES A PROGRAM RECIPIENT’S ELIGIBILITY TO

4 SENATE BILL 742
1 CONTINUE TO RECEIVE SERVICES USING EXISTING DATA, WITHOUT REQUIRING THE
2 PROGRAM RECIPIENT TO SUBMIT ADDITIONAL INFORMATION.
3 (3) “HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES” MEANS SERVICES
4 AUTHORIZED UNDER A MEDICAID STATE PLAN OPTION OR WAIVER UNDER § 1115
5 OR § 1915(C), (I), OR (K) OF THE FEDERAL SOCIAL SECURITY ACT.
6 (4) “PROCEDURAL DISENROLLMENT” MEANS THE TERMINATION OF A
7 PROGRAM RECIPIENT’S ELIGIBILITY TO RECEIVE SERVICES BASED ON REASONS
8 RELATED TO THE RENEWAL PROCESS AND NOT ON A DETERMINATION OF
9 INELIGIBILITY.
10 (B) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL COMPLY WITH THE REQUIREMENTS OF 42
11 C.F.R. § 435.912 RELATED TO THE TIMELY DETERMINATION AND
12 REDETERMINATION OF PROGRAM ELIGIBILITY, INCLUDING PROCESSING AN
13 APPLICATION:
14 (1) IF A DETERMINATION OF DISABILITY IS NOT REQUIRED, WITHIN
15 45 DAYS AFTER THE RECEIPT OF THE APPLICATION; AND
16 (2) IF A DETERMINATION OF DISABILITY IS REQUIRED, WITHIN 90
17 DAYS AFTER THE RECEIPT OF THE APPLICATION.
18 (C) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL CONDUCT EX PARTE REDETERMINATIONS
19 AND USE ALL PROCEDURES AUTHORIZED UNDER 42 C.F.R. § 435.916 TO PREVENT
20 PROCEDURAL DISENROLLMENT OF INDIVIDUALS RECEIVING HOME– AND
21 COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES.
22 (D) IN ACCORDANCE WITH 42 C.F.R. § 435.905 AND SUBJECT TO
23 SUBSECTION (E) OF THIS SECTION, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PROVIDE, IN
24 ELECTRONIC AND PAPER FORMATS, AND ORALLY AS APPROPRIATE AN
25 ACCOMMODATION, THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION TO ALL APPLICANTS AND OTHER
26 INDIVIDUALS ON REQUEST:
27 (1) REQUIREMENTS FOR PROGRAM ELIGIBILITY;
28 (2) AVAILABLE PROGRAM SERVICES; AND
29 (3) THE RIGHTS AND RESPONSIBILITIES OF APPLICANTS AND
30 PROGRAM RECIPIENTS.

SENATE BILL 742 5
1 (E) (1) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PROVIDE THE INFORMATION
2 REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION (D) OF THIS SECTION IN PLAIN LANGUAGE AND IN A
3 MANNER THAT IS TIMELY AND ACCESSIBLE TO INDIVIDUALS WHO ARE:
4 (I) LIMITED ENGLISH PROFICIENT THROUGH THE PROVISION
5 OF LANGUAGE SERVICES, INCLUDING ORAL INTERPRETATION AND WRITTEN
6 TRANSLATIONS, AT NO COST TO THE INDIVIDUAL; OR
7 (II) LIVING WITH DISABILITIES THROUGH THE PROVISION OF
8 AUXILIARY AIDS AND SERVICES AT NO COST TO THE INDIVIDUAL IN ACCORDANCE
9 WITH THE FEDERAL AMERICANS WITH DISABILITIES ACT AND § 504 OF THE
10 FEDERAL REHABILITATION ACT OF 1973.
11 (2) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PROVIDE TAGLINES IN NON–ENGLISH
12 LANGUAGES TO INFORM INDIVIDUALS OF:
13 (I) THE AVAILABILITY OF THE ACCESSIBLE INFORMATION AND
14 LANGUAGE SERVICES UNDER THIS SECTION; AND
15 (II) HOW TO ACCESS THE INFORMATION AND SERVICES.
16 (F) IF THE DEPARTMENT DETERMINES THAT THE INFORMATION
17 NECESSARY TO CONFIRM A PROGRAM RECIPIENT’S ELIGIBILITY TO CONTINUE TO
18 RECEIVE SERVICES IS INCOMPLETE, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL CONTINUE TO
19 PROVIDE THE HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES AND OTHER SERVICES
20 UNDER THE PROGRAM UNTIL THE PROGRAM RECIPIENT HAS EXHAUSTED ALL DUE
21 PROCESS RIGHTS AND A FINAL DETERMINATION IS ISSUED.
22 (G) (1) IF A PROGRAM RECIPIENT IS PROCEDURALLY DISENROLLED
23 FROM HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES DUE TO A FAILURE BY THE
24 DEPARTMENT TO REDETERMINE ELIGIBILITY IN A TIMELY MANNER AND THE DELAY
25 IN THE REDETERMINATION WAS NO FAULT OF THE PROGRAM RECIPIENT, THE
26 DEPARTMENT SHALL REINSTATE THE PROGRAM RECIPIENT’S ELIGIBILITY AND THE
27 PROVISION OF HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES AND AUTHORIZE
28 ENROLLMENT RETROACTIVELY TO THE DATE OF DISENROLLMENT PENDING THE
29 DEPARTMENT’S COMPLETION OF THE REDETERMINATION PROCESS.
30 (2) THIS SUBSECTION MAY NOT BE CONSTRUED TO LIMIT THE
31 DEPARTMENT’S AUTHORITY OR DIMINISH THE DEPARTMENT’S RESPONSIBILITY TO
32 REINSTATE THE ELIGIBILITY OF AND THE PROVISION OF HOME– AND
33 COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES TO A PROGRAM RECIPIENT WHO HAS BEEN
34 DISENROLLED FOR A REASON OTHER THAN A FAILURE BY THE DEPARTMENT TO
35 REDETERMINE ELIGIBILITY IN A TIMELY MANNER.

6 SENATE BILL 742
1 (H) (G) SUBJECT TO FEDERAL APPROVAL, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL
2 RESERVE A PORTION OF THE PARTICIPANT CAPACITY IN THE HOME– AND
3 COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES WAIVER UNDER § 1915(C) OF THE FEDERAL SOCIAL
4 SECURITY ACT WAIVERS FOR SERVICES NEEDED BY PROGRAM RECIPIENTS WITH
5 DEVELOPMENTAL DISABILITIES WHO:
6 (1) WERE DISENROLLED FROM THE MARYLAND MEDICAID HOME
7 AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES WAIVER PROGRAM ON OR AFTER JANUARY 1,
8 2024;
9 (2) HAVE HAD PROGRAM ELIGIBILITY REINSTATED; AND
10 (3) HAVE REQUESTED THE REINSTATEMENT OF WAIVER SERVICES.
11 (I) THE DEPARTMENT MAY NOT PLACE AN INDIVIDUAL ON A WAITING LIST
12 OR REQUIRE A NEW WAIVER APPLICATION IF THE DISENROLLMENT OF THE
13 INDIVIDUAL RESULTED FROM A DELAY OR AN ERROR BY THE DEPARTMENT.
14 (J) (H) (1) THE DEPARTMENT MAY NOT PROCEDURALLY DISENROLL
15 AN INDIVIDUAL FROM THE PROGRAM OR HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES
16 SOLELY BASED ON MISSING DOCUMENTATION, A MISSING SIGNATURE, OR
17 INCOMPLETE INFORMATION UNLESS THE DEPARTMENT HAS:
18 (I) EXHAUSTED ALL EX PARTE VERIFICATION PROCESSES
19 REQUIRED UNDER 42 C.F.R. § 435.916;
20 (II) PROVIDED A CLEAR, SPECIFIC, AND ACCESSIBLE WRITTEN
21 NOTICE IDENTIFYING THE EXACT INFORMATION REQUIRED;
22 (III) PROVIDED THE PROGRAM RECIPIENT WITH A REASONABLE
23 OPPORTUNITY TO SUPPLY THE INFORMATION; AND
24 (IV) VERIFIED THAT THE INDIVIDUAL RECEIVED THE NOTICE
25 REQUIRED UNDER ITEM (II) OF THIS PARAGRAPH AND DOCUMENTED THE
26 VERIFICATION.
27 (2) IF THE DEPARTMENT VIOLATES PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
28 SUBSECTION, A PROGRAM RECIPIENT’S HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES
29 SHALL CONTINUE WITHOUT INTERRUPTION.
30 (K) (I) IF THE DEPARTMENT DISENROLLS A PROGRAM RECIPIENT IN
31 VIOLATION OF THIS SECTION, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL:

SENATE BILL 742 7
1 (1) AUTOMATICALLY REINSTATE PROGRAM AND HOME– AND
2 COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES RETROACTIVE TO THE DATE OF DISENROLLMENT;
3 AND
4 (2) TREAT THE PROGRAM RECIPIENT AS CONTINUOUSLY ENROLLED.
5 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Laws of Maryland read
6 as follows:
7 Article – Health – General
8 15–103.9.
9 (L) (J) (1) ON OR BEFORE JANUARY 1, 2027, AND QUARTERLY
10 THEREAFTER, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL:
11 (I) SUBMIT TO THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY, IN ACCORDANCE
12 WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, A REPORT REGARDING
13 PROGRAM RECIPIENTS WHO RECEIVE HOME– AND COMMUNITY–BASED SERVICES;
14 AND
15 (II) POST EACH REPORT SUBMITTED UNDER ITEM (I) OF THIS
16 PARAGRAPH ON THE DEPARTMENT’S WEBSITE.
17 (2) THE REPORTS REQUIRED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
18 SUBSECTION SHALL INCLUDE:
19 (I) THE TOTAL NUMBER OF PROGRAM RECIPIENTS FOR WHOM
20 A REDETERMINATION OF ELIGIBILITY WAS INITIATED;
21 (II) THE TOTAL NUMBER OF PROGRAM RECIPIENTS FOR WHOM
22 PROGRAM COVERAGE IS RENEWED;
23 (III) OF THE PROGRAM RECIPIENTS WHOSE ELIGIBILITY IS
24 RENEWED, THE TOTAL NUMBER WHOSE COVERAGE WAS RENEWED BASED ON AN EX
25 PARTE REDETERMINATION;
26 (IV) THE TOTAL NUMBER OF PROGRAM RECIPIENTS WHOSE
27 ELIGIBILITY WAS REINSTATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH SUBSECTION (F) OF THIS
28 SECTION;
29 (IV) (V) THE TOTAL NUMBER OF PROGRAM RECIPIENTS
30 WHOSE ELIGIBILITY WAS TERMINATED;

8 SENATE BILL 742
1 (V) (VI) THE TOTAL NUMBER OF PROGRAM RECIPIENTS
2 WHOSE ELIGIBILITY WAS TERMINATED FOR PROCEDURAL REASONS;
3 (VII) THE TOTAL NUMBER OF PROGRAM RECIPIENTS WHOSE
4 ELIGIBILITY WAS TERMINATED DUE TO A FAILURE BY THE DEPARTMENT TO
5 REDETERMINE ELIGIBILITY IN A TIMELY MANNER; AND
6 (VI) (VIII) THE MEAN AND MEDIAN PROCESSING TIMES FOR
7 REDETERMINATIONS OF ELIGIBILITY.
8 SECTION 2. 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
9 October 1, 2026. Section 2 of this Act shall remain effective for a period of 3 years and, at
10 the end of September 30, 2029, Section 2 of this Act, with no further action required by the
11 General Assembly, shall be abrogated and of no further force and effect.
Approved:
